<body>
  <a class="skip-link" href="#main-content">Skip to main content</a>
  <div id="live-region" role="status" aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true"></div>
  <header role="banner">
    <div class="app-header">
      <p class="eyebrow">HLTH 207 &middot; Public and Population Health</p>
      <h1>Core Functions Match</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Match each essential service to its core public health function</p>
    </div>
  </header>
  <main id="main-content">
    <div class="app-wrap">

      <!-- WELCOME SCREEN -->
      <section id="screen-welcome" class="screen active" aria-labelledby="welcome-title">
        <div class="welcome-box">
          <h2 id="welcome-title">How to Use This Activity</h2>
          <p>Public health is built on three core functions defined by the Institute of Medicine. Every one of the 10 essential public health services falls under one of these functions. Your task is to match each service to the right one.</p>
          <p>This activity is more urgent than it might seem. Right now, in 2026, each of these 10 services is under direct pressure from federal budget cuts, workforce reductions, and agency restructuring. Understanding which function each service belongs to will help you see exactly where the gaps are forming.</p>

          <div class="stat-callout" role="note" aria-label="Current public health context">
            <span class="stat-num" aria-hidden="true">53%</span>
            <span class="stat-text"><strong>Proposed FY 2026 CDC budget cut</strong> if enacted. The CDC lost roughly a quarter of its workforce by the end of 2025, including over 1,000 scientists, physicians, and public health specialists. About 80% of CDC's domestic budget flows directly to state and local health departments. Source: Trust for America's Health, 2025.</span>
          </div>

          <div class="function-intro" role="list" aria-label="The three core functions of public health">
            <div class="function-intro-card assess" role="listitem">
              <p class="fn-name">Assessment</p>
              <p>Collecting and analyzing data to understand the health of populations, identify health problems, and generate the evidence base for action.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="function-intro-card policy" role="listitem">
              <p class="fn-name">Policy Development</p>
              <p>Using evidence to inform, educate, and mobilize communities and policymakers toward health-protective policies and plans.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="function-intro-card assure" role="listitem">
              <p class="fn-name">Assurance</p>
              <p>Ensuring that all people can access necessary health services and that the workforce, laws, and systems to deliver those services are in place and functioning.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>For each of the 10 essential services, select Assessment, Policy Development, or Assurance. After you submit, you will see an explanation for each one that connects to what is happening in public health right now.</p>

          <div class="advocacy-prompt" role="note">
            <p class="ap-label">Health Advocacy Project Connection</p>
            <p>As you work through this activity, ask yourself: which core function does your senator letter address? Most policy advocacy letters call on legislators to take action within the Policy Development function, but they must be grounded in Assessment evidence and must ultimately demand Assurance results.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="btn-row">
            <button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" id="btn-start" aria-label="Start the Core Functions Match activity">
              Start Activity
            </button>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- QUIZ SCREEN -->
      <section id="screen-quiz" class="screen" aria-labelledby="quiz-title">
        <h2 id="quiz-title" class="sr-only">Core Functions Match — Answer all 10 services</h2>
        <div class="progress-wrap" role="group" aria-label="Activity progress">
          <p class="progress-label" id="progress-text" aria-live="polite">0 of 10 answered</p>
          <div class="progress-bar-bg" role="progressbar" aria-valuenow="0" aria-valuemin="0" aria-valuemax="10" aria-labelledby="progress-text" id="progress-bar-wrap">
            <div class="progress-bar-fill" id="progress-bar"></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="quiz-intro">
          <strong>Instructions:</strong> For each essential public health service below, select the core function it belongs to:
          <span style="color:var(--assess-dark);font-weight:bold;">Assessment</span>,
          <span style="color:var(--policy-dark);font-weight:bold;">Policy Development</span>, or
          <span style="color:var(--assure-dark);font-weight:bold;">Assurance</span>.
        </p>
        <div id="cards-container" role="list" aria-label="10 essential public health services to categorize"></div>
        <div class="submit-row" role="group" aria-label="Submission controls">
          <p class="answer-count" aria-live="polite" id="answered-count">
            <strong id="answered-num">0</strong> of 10 answered
          </p>
          <button class="btn btn-primary" id="btn-submit" aria-label="Check all answers">Check Answers</button>
          <button class="btn btn-secondary" id="btn-clear" aria-label="Clear all selections and start over">Clear All</button>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- RESULTS SCREEN -->
      <section id="screen-results" class="screen" aria-labelledby="results-title">
        <div class="results-header" role="region" aria-labelledby="results-title">
          <h2 id="results-title">Your Results</h2>
          <p class="score-display" id="score-display" aria-label="Score">&mdash;</p>
          <p class="score-label" id="score-label">out of 10 correct</p>
          <p id="score-message" style="margin-top:.5rem;font-size:1rem;color:#C8E6C9;"></p>
        </div>
        <div class="function-summary" role="list" aria-label="Results grouped by core function">
          <div class="fn-summary-card assess" role="listitem">
            <p class="fn-title">Assessment (2 services)</p>
            <p class="fn-services" id="assess-services"></p>
          </div>
          <div class="fn-summary-card policy" role="listitem">
            <p class="fn-title">Policy Development (3 services)</p>
            <p class="fn-services" id="policy-services"></p>
          </div>
          <div class="fn-summary-card assure" role="listitem">
            <p class="fn-title">Assurance (5 services)</p>
            <p class="fn-services" id="assure-services"></p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="results-detail">
          <h3>Detailed Results</h3>
          <div id="results-list" role="list" aria-label="Detailed results for each service"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="project-connection" role="region" aria-labelledby="project-connection-title">
          <h3 id="project-connection-title">Health Advocacy Project Connection</h3>
          <div class="project-stage">
            <p class="stage-label">Stage 1: Identify Your Issue</p>
            <p>Now that you can classify the 10 essential services, where does your policy topic fit? Is the gap an Assessment problem (we lack data or surveillance), a Policy Development problem (we lack the right laws or community engagement), or an Assurance problem (people cannot access services that already exist in policy)?</p>
          </div>
          <div class="project-stage">
            <p class="stage-label">Stage 2: Article Reviews</p>
            <p>When you read your three peer-reviewed articles, look for which core function the researchers are addressing. Papers that describe disease burden or health disparities are building the Assessment case. Papers that evaluate program reach or service gaps are addressing Assurance. Papers about policy design or advocacy strategy fall under Policy Development.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="project-stage">
            <p class="stage-label">Stage 3: Senator Letter</p>
            <p>Your letter is itself a Policy Development action. You are informing a policymaker and mobilizing them toward change. Frame your opening argument using Assessment data, identify the Assurance failure your community is experiencing, and propose a Policy Development solution the senator can act on.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="project-stage">
            <p class="stage-label">Stage 4: Presentation</p>
            <p>Structure your presentation around all three functions: open with Assessment evidence that shows the problem, move to the Policy Development gap that allowed it to persist, and close with an Assurance commitment the senator must make to fix it. This three-act structure is the most persuasive framework in public health advocacy.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:1.5rem;">
          <button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" id="btn-retry" aria-label="Try the activity again with cleared answers">Try Again</button>
          <button class="btn btn-secondary" id="btn-back-welcome" aria-label="Return to the activity introduction">Back to Start</button>
        </div>
      </section>

